{"source_key":"sha256-852da461b9759bc2736926d9891eb9a3","record_index":2519,"record_hash":"sha256:39ffc72dcff579632887b8cbcf4df402a0491e569dc4b6a91633531dc990d99f","timestamp":"2026-05-20T06:12:50.783Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: e81ce6\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 4145\nOutput:\n\nDo not persist automatic scoring results as durable relationships in v1. They\nshould be derived read-time results with a scoring version, confidence label,\nand reasons. A future cache is fine if it is explicitly rebuildable derived\ndata.\n\nSuggested result shape:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"session_key\": \"sha256-...\",\n  \"turn_keys\": [\"sha256-...\"],\n  \"score\": 82,\n  \"confidence\": \"high\",\n  \"reasons\": [\n    {\n      \"kind\": \"previous_worktree_files_committed\",\n      \"turn_key\": \"sha256-...\",\n      \"matched_paths\": [\"src/foo.rs\"],\n      \"matched_path_count\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"kind\": \"observed_review\",\n      \"turn_key\": \"sha256-...\",\n      \"review_key\": \"github-pr:owner/repo#1284\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"scoring_version\": \"agentlog-association.v1\"\n}\n```\n\nThe exact numeric scale can change, but the first heuristic should be simple and\nexplainable:\n\n- explicit user/API relationships, if they exist, win\n- previous worktree files later appearing in observed commits is strong evidence\n- observed review id, pull request, or change id is strong candidate evidence\n- observed branch name is useful candidate evidence but weak on its own\n- repeated observation across many turns strengthens a session-level result\n- broad or truncated file lists weaken file-overlap evidence\n- multiple visible branches/stacks weaken branch-name evidence\n- missing or failed environment snapshots simply produce less evidence\n\nUse confidence buckets for product behavior, with numeric scores only as an\ninternal sorting aid:\n\n- `high`: show automatically as likely related\n- `medium`: show as possibly related or secondary context\n- `low`: hide by default, but keep available for debugging or expanded context\n- `none`: no meaningful signal\n\nInitial v1 bucket rules should stay conservative:\n\n- direct change-id observation is high confidence\n- previous-turn worktree files later appearing in commit files on the queried\n  target is high confidence\n- direct review or pul\n[TRUNCATED]\n = failed`.\n- Capture must use either a repo/session capture lock or optimistic retry around\n  dedupe, previous-turn lookup, and the atomic write.\n- Automatic association is private discovery. Review sharing needs an explicit\n  projection/redaction step before transcript records, tool payloads, paths, or\n  environment details are exposed outside normal repository-private scope.\n\n## Later Questions\n\n- Should future relationship metadata support target-to-session links with\n  optional turn scope, and what should that shape be?\n- If durable explicit relationships are added later, should branch and PR views\n  derive them from lower-level change/review links, or should metadata be copied\n  upward?\n- How should commits, rebases, squashes, and branch rewrites outside GitButler\n  affect turn-derived evidence, if at all?\n\n## Implementation Implications\n\nThe current implementation in `crates/but-agentlog` already has the pieces that\nmake a capture turn layer plausible:\n\n- `record_transcript` snapshots a transcript file\n- `TranscriptBatch::parse` returns parsed records plus session/source metadata\n- `write_transcript_batch` filters records through `:record-hashes`\n- transcript records already carry `source_key`, `record_index`, and\n  `record_hash`\n\nThe missing piece is that `write_transcript_batch` throws away the batch\nboundary after appending records. A capture turn writer would need to receive\nthe set of newly accepted records and write a corresponding capture turn object.\n\n`but-agentlog` should probably become a higher-level GitButler crate for this\nfeature and depend on other `but-*` crates instead of reimplementing workspace\ninspection. The likely shape is:\n\n- depend on `but-ctx` so capture can build the same repository/workspace context\n  as the rest of GitButler\n- prefer reusable `but-api` entry points when they already provide the product\n  shape we need\n- use a lower-level path-only worktree snapshot helper for uncommitted files;\n  avoid UI diff APIs that compute hunks, ownership, assignments, or dependency\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T06:12:50.783Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}